+---
+title: Execution patterns
+description: How queue-level execution patterns (static-dag, pipeline, map-reduce) layer above the engine tick loop — pattern config, the gate/respawn circle-back, extendRun + run.extended audit entries, and the forward-arc-never-rewind invariant.
+---
+
+The core orchestrator engine is deliberately narrow: it schedules a fixed DAG,
+polls running items via reconcile, and moves each item through a defined status
+lattice. That model covers a large class of work, but some jobs are structurally
+dynamic — the exact set of items is only knowable once earlier items run. Rather
+than complicate the engine, pangolin-scale layers **execution patterns** on top of it: a
+per-queue strategy object that observes terminal items after each tick and may
+answer with new work to add to the same run.
+
+For the tick loop that patterns plug into, see
+[How an offload run executes](/pangolin/explanation/how-offload-runs/). For the
+shape of a plan, see the [plan.json reference](/pangolin/reference/plan-json/). This
+page is about what happens *above* the engine between ticks.
+
+## What an execution pattern is
+
+An execution pattern is a pure, stateless strategy object registered on a queue.
+It is not a new trigger, a separate queue, or a parallel scheduler — it is a
+**post-tick hook** on a single queue. After the engine tick for that queue
+finishes, the orchestrator runs a **pattern phase**:
+
+1. Collect every unsealed run on the queue.
+2. For each run, call `pattern.inspect(run)` — a pure function that sees the
+   current item statuses and their `outputs`.
+3. If `inspect` returns a non-empty spawn directive, apply it through the
+   audited `extendRun` seam.
+4. Check whether the run has settled and the pattern has no more spawns to issue;
+   if yes, seal the run. A run that just received new items cannot seal in the
+   same pattern phase.
+
+Because patterns are pure and keep no state of their own, the same `inspect`
+call is safe to repeat after a crash — the spawn directive is derived fresh from
+the run's current item set every time.
+
+## Queue-level pattern config
+
+Patterns are declared per-queue in `pangolin.config.ts`. A queue without a pattern
+entry uses the engine's default behavior — a static DAG submitted at
+`pangolin orch submit` time and never extended.
+
+```ts
+// pangolin.config.ts
+queues: [
+  {
+    name: 'default',
+    concurrency: 4,
+  },
+  {
+    name: 'etl',
+    concurrency: 8,
+    pattern: { type: 'map-reduce' },
+  },
+  {
+    name: 'review',
+    concurrency: 2,
+    pattern: { type: 'pipeline' },
+  },
+]
+```
+
+Three pattern types ship with the orchestrator:
+
+| Pattern | When to use |
+|---|---|
+| `static-dag` | The full item graph is known at submit time. This is the default; it opts into explicit pattern machinery without enabling dynamic spawning. |
+| `pipeline` | A sequence of named stages where a gate item may fail and a later stage may circle back to retry from an earlier point. |
+| `map-reduce` | A splitter item emits a variable-length list of keys into `outputs/`, and the pattern spawns one mapper item per key, then a single reducer after all mappers finish. |
+
+The config field accepts an optional `options` object for pattern-specific
+parameters — for example, `map-reduce` accepts `mapExecutor` and
+`reduceExecutor` to name the capability to dispatch for each role.
+
+## The gate/respawn circle-back
+
+A **gate** is a pipeline stage item whose job is to inspect the output of the
+preceding stage and decide whether the run should continue, retry, or abort. A
+gate that succeeds unblocks the next stage as a normal `depends_on` edge. A gate
+that fails is where the circle-back mechanic applies.
+
+When a gate item reaches `failed` and the pipeline pattern's retry budget is not
+yet exhausted, the pattern's `inspect` call returns a **respawn directive**: a
+fresh lineage of stage items, starting from the stage the gate specified in its
+`outputs/retry-from` sentinel, with `depends_on` pointing at the *original*
+upstream items (not the failed gate). The failed gate branch stays in the run as
+sealed history — its status is `failed` and it never becomes `done`.
+
+From the engine's perspective nothing special happens: `extendRun` appends new
+items whose `depends_on` edges are all already terminal `done` items, so they
+immediately become `ready` on the next tick's ready phase and proceed normally.
+The pattern has produced a second arc through the same logical stages without
+touching any already-finished work.
+
+A practical example: a `lint` stage produces a patch, a `review-gate` inspects
+it, finds a style violation, and fails with `outputs/retry-from: lint`. The
+pattern spawns a new `lint-2` item (with the fix prompt adjusted via
+`outputs/retry-hint`) and a new `review-gate-2`. If `review-gate-2` passes, the
+pipeline proceeds. If the retry budget is exhausted, the run settles as `failed`
+and no more spawns are issued.
+
+```mermaid
+stateDiagram-v2
+  direction LR
+  [*] --> lint
+  lint --> review_gate
+  review_gate --> done: pass
+  review_gate --> lint_2: fail + retry budget > 0\n(extendRun respawn)
+  lint_2 --> review_gate_2
+  review_gate_2 --> done: pass
+  review_gate_2 --> failed: budget exhausted
+```
+
+The `review_gate` node above stays `failed` in the run forever — the diagram
+shows logical flow, not a status transition.
+
+## extendRun and the run.extended audit entry
+
+All dynamic item addition goes through a single audited seam: `extendRun`. This
+is not a backdoor around the engine — it is the same `validateRun` call that
+`submitRun` uses, applied to the *merged* graph (existing items plus proposed
+new items). If the merged graph would be invalid — a dependency on a
+non-existent item, a cycle, a duplicate id — the spawn is rejected and the
+pattern's directive is dropped as if it returned empty.
+
+When `extendRun` succeeds it writes a `run.extended` audit entry before the
+engine sees the new items:
+
+```json
+{
+  "type": "run.extended",
+  "runId": "etl-run-20260607",
+  "actor": "pattern:etl",
+  "causeItemId": "splitter",
+  "spawnedItemIds": ["map-file-a", "map-file-b", "map-file-c", "reduce"],
+  "ts": "2026-06-07T03:41:02.114Z"
+}
+```
+
+`actor` is always `pattern:<queueName>` — the pattern acted, not a human.
+`causeItemId` names the terminal item whose `outputs` triggered the spawn.
+`spawnedItemIds` is the complete list of new item ids added in this call. Because
+one `extendRun` call is atomic (a single DB transaction), a partial crash cannot
+produce a run with items that have no `run.extended` record.
+
+The audit entry is written unconditionally before any engine tick sees the new
+items, so `pangolin verify`'s provenance closure covers dynamically grown graphs
+without any new verification logic: every item in the final graph either appears
+in the original `run.submitted` entry or in exactly one `run.extended` entry.
+
+## The forward-arc-never-rewind invariant
+
+The central safety property of dynamic spawning is simple: **spawned items may
+only `depends_on` items that already exist in the run at spawn time.** Patterns
+cannot express a dependency on an item that does not yet exist, and they cannot
+modify an item that is already in the run. The graph grows forward; it never
+mutates backward.
+
+This invariant is enforced by `validateRun` on the merged graph:
+
+- Every id in any item's `depends_on` must resolve to an item present in the
+  merged item list before the transaction commits. A `depends_on` that names
+  a not-yet-spawned future item fails validation and the whole directive is
+  rejected.
+- Item ids must be unique across the merged graph. Patterns that generate
+  deterministic ids (e.g. `map-${fileKey}`) are idempotent: a re-inspect after
+  a crash re-derives the same ids, `extendRun` finds them already present, and
+  the validation succeeds with a no-op.
+
+Three consequences follow from the invariant:
+
+**No cycles, ever.** Because spawned items only point backward, there is no way
+to construct a cycle through `extendRun`. The DAG stays a DAG across every spawn,
+and the engine's dependency resolver requires no cycle-detection on the hot path.
+
+**Circle-back is new lineage, not rewind.** The "respawn from stage N" pattern
+described above does not re-run or mutate stage N's original item — it appends a
+new item `stage-N-2` whose `depends_on` edges point at the items that the
+*original* stage N depended on. The failed arc is permanent sealed history;
+`pangolin verify` will always report that `review-gate` failed. The new arc's
+provenance is fully separate.
+
+**Settled state is monotone.** An item that reaches a terminal status
+(`done`, `failed`, `skipped`, `cancelled`) never changes status. Patterns
+observe terminal items but cannot un-terminal them. A run's sealed history is
+therefore append-only: `run.extended` entries accumulate; they never revise.
+
+Together these properties mean the orchestrator's audit guarantees extend to
+dynamically grown runs without special-casing: `pangolin verify` treats the full
+merged graph as the canonical graph and checks provenance closure over it.
+
+## Replay safety and determinism
+
+Because `inspect` is a pure function with no external state, patterns are
+replay-safe by construction. If the orchestrator crashes between writing a
+`run.extended` entry and ticking the engine, the next startup's pattern phase
+re-inspects the same run, derives the same spawn directive, calls `extendRun`
+again, and the transaction is a no-op — the ids already exist. No items are
+duplicated, no audit entries are doubled.
+
+Spawn id determinism is the pattern author's responsibility, not the engine's.
+The built-in `map-reduce` pattern derives mapper ids as `map-${hashOfFileKey}`
+so they are stable across re-inspections. Custom patterns should follow the same
+convention: compute ids from the cause item's outputs, not from a
+process-global counter or wall-clock time.
